# Immutability by Default
- `val` everywhere; `var` only inside a tight, isolated local scope.
- Public APIs return read-only `List`/`Set`/`Map` — never `MutableList` etc.
- State holders expose immutable views (`StateFlow<T>`, not `MutableStateFlow<T>`).

# Domain Modeling
- Use **data classes** for state; their `equals`/`hashCode`/`copy` are required for diffing and `StateFlow` distinctness.
- Replace primitive obsession with **inline/value classes** for IDs and units.

```kotlin
@JvmInline value class UserId(val raw: String)
@JvmInline value class FocusMinutes(val value: Int)

data class FocusSession(val id: UserId, val duration: FocusMinutes, val startedAt: Instant)
```

- Model finite outcomes with **sealed interfaces**, not booleans + nullables.

```kotlin
sealed interface LoadResult<out T> {
    data class Success<T>(val value: T) : LoadResult<T>
    data class Failure(val error: Throwable) : LoadResult<Nothing>
}
```

# Separation of Concerns
- **Composable**: render state, emit events. No I/O, no business logic.
- **ViewModel**: orchestrate use cases, expose `StateFlow`. No Android UI imports (`androidx.compose.*`, `View`, `Context`).
- **Repository / UseCase**: data access and domain rules. No `viewModelScope`, no UI types.
- One-way data flow: `UI → events → ViewModel → state → UI`.

# Side-Effect Boundaries
- Side effects (logging, navigation, toasts) live in `LaunchedEffect` / collectors, never inside `remember` blocks or composition itself.
- `remember { }` must be pure; no I/O, no mutation of external state.
